43
00:00:20,430 --> 00:00:22,180
So, why do I need to quit my job to have a family?

44
00:00:22,180 --> 00:00:24,410
Agreed. She can be a great lawyer and a great mom.

45
00:00:24,410 --> 00:00:25,830
I don't want to have kids.

46
00:00:25,830 --> 00:00:27,460
I don't need a therapist.

47
00:00:27,470 --> 00:00:29,050
I want to make my own decisions.

48
00:00:29,060 --> 00:00:30,590
I am done talking.

49
00:00:30,590 --> 00:00:31,910
- Now let's go. - ‭No. N-No.

50
00:00:31,910 --> 00:00:32,640
I don't want help!

51
00:00:32,640 --> 00:00:33,370
Where would he go?

52
00:00:33,370 --> 00:00:34,810
Is there a place he likes to hang out?

53
00:00:34,810 --> 00:00:36,050
I mean, he's not at the hospital.

54
00:00:36,050 --> 00:00:37,660
And there used to be a picture here.

55
00:00:37,660 --> 00:00:39,260
It means he's not coming back.

56
00:00:42,650 --> 00:00:43,710
Hi. Good morning.

57
00:00:43,710 --> 00:00:45,750
I'm Aaron Glassman. Dr. Glassman.

58
00:00:45,750 --> 00:00:47,100
I work with Shaun.

59
00:00:47,100 --> 00:00:48,870
Hi. Nice to meet you.

60
00:00:48,870 --> 00:00:51,280
It's nice to meet you, too. May I speak with him, please?

61
00:00:52,640 --> 00:00:54,080
Shaun isn't here.

62
00:00:54,640 --> 00:00:58,100
I know you've been helping Shaun, and I appreciate that,

63
00:00:58,750 --> 00:01:01,030
but I really need to speak with him immediately.

64
00:01:01,400 --> 00:01:04,210
I'll definitely let him know when I see him next.

65
00:01:05,340 --> 00:01:06,530
I'm -- I'm sorry.

66
00:01:06,560 --> 00:01:07,410
What the hell are you doing?

67
00:01:07,410 --> 00:01:08,680
Shaun, I know you're in here.

68
00:01:08,680 --> 00:01:11,000
I just -- I just want to talk, please.

69
00:01:11,080 --> 00:01:12,410
You are way out of line.

70
00:01:12,410 --> 00:01:14,740
Shaun, you have responsibilities.

71
00:01:14,980 --> 00:01:16,190
We've got to sort this out.

72
00:01:16,190 --> 00:01:17,670
You have five seconds to get the hell out of here...

73
00:01:17,670 --> 00:01:19,220
- Shaun. - or I'm calling the police.

74
00:01:19,220 --> 00:01:20,550
- Shaun, I just -- - What are --

75
00:01:20,800 --> 00:01:22,060
I just want to...

76
00:01:23,470 --> 00:01:25,550
- Five... - Shaun.

77
00:01:26,170 --> 00:01:27,530
Shaun, she's calling the police.

78
00:01:27,530 --> 00:01:29,000
- four... - Is that what you want?

79
00:01:29,010 --> 00:01:29,870
three...

80
00:01:30,670 --> 00:01:31,800
- two... - Okay, okay.

81
00:01:31,800 --> 00:01:33,850
- one. - Okay, okay, I'm leaving.

82
00:01:34,270 --> 00:01:37,870
It's just that Shaun has a-a tendency to run away from conflict.

83
00:01:37,870 --> 00:01:40,010
And in Casper and medical school,

84
00:01:40,010 --> 00:01:42,380
people will give you a little bit of slack, but it --

85
00:01:42,380 --> 00:01:44,060
now he's in a very hard-to-get job

86
00:01:44,060 --> 00:01:45,960
in a very competitive environment

87
00:01:45,960 --> 00:01:48,170
where people do not give you a second chance.

88
00:01:49,090 --> 00:01:51,560
Still, not cool.

89
00:01:56,390 --> 00:02:00,510
If you speak with him will you call me, please?

90
00:02:00,910 --> 00:02:01,770
Out.

91
00:02:04,150 --> 00:02:05,010
Yeah.

92
00:02:17,520 --> 00:02:18,680
So, what's your plan now?

93
00:02:21,840 --> 00:02:22,860
I don't know.

94
00:02:34,740 --> 00:02:37,410
I gotta say, he seems like a nebby, old jerk.

95
00:02:37,410 --> 00:02:38,180
And a bully.

96
00:02:38,180 --> 00:02:39,850
What's "Nebby"?

97
00:02:39,850 --> 00:02:42,210
Nosey. It's a Pittsburgh thing.

98
00:02:42,370 --> 00:02:43,910
I mean, you're a grown man.

99
00:02:43,910 --> 00:02:46,570
If you don't want to talk to him, it's none of his business.

100
00:02:46,970 --> 00:02:50,410
San Jose is too big.

101
00:02:50,920 --> 00:02:52,850
I get not liking San Jose.

102
00:02:52,850 --> 00:02:54,170
I'm not the biggest fan myself, but --

103
00:02:54,170 --> 00:02:57,290
I don't want to see a therapist.

104
00:02:57,410 --> 00:02:58,440
So don't.

105
00:03:01,050 --> 00:03:03,770
I should go back to Casper.

106
00:03:03,970 --> 00:03:04,920
I have a rule.

107
00:03:05,170 --> 00:03:08,420
Never make an important decision while you are angry,

108
00:03:08,420 --> 00:03:12,570
upset, high, or right before or after having sex.

109
00:03:12,820 --> 00:03:15,060
Okay, you are overworked, stressed out,

110
00:03:15,060 --> 00:03:16,350
and pissed off at your boss.

111
00:03:16,350 --> 00:03:19,070
Now is not the time to be making a big decision.

112
00:03:19,320 --> 00:03:22,470
You need to take a break, clear your head.

113
00:03:22,630 --> 00:03:23,760
You need a vacation.

114
00:03:23,760 --> 00:03:28,040
I have to work five more months before I earn a vacation.

115
00:03:28,050 --> 00:03:29,290
So call in sick.

116
00:03:30,110 --> 00:03:32,070
I'm not sick.

117
00:03:32,800 --> 00:03:33,950
You're so adorable.

118
00:03:33,950 --> 00:03:37,170
You don't have to be sick to call in sick.

119
00:03:37,470 --> 00:03:39,420
Ah, I have so much to teach you, Grasshopper.

120
00:03:39,430 --> 00:03:42,550
And I'm gonna start with a good, old-fashioned road trip.

121
00:03:42,550 --> 00:03:44,360
It's the perfect way to get your mojo back.

122
00:03:44,360 --> 00:03:45,280
And when we return,

123
00:03:45,280 --> 00:03:47,180
you're gonna know exactly what to do about

124
00:03:47,220 --> 00:03:50,480
San Jose, therapy, and Glassy the Grouch.

125
00:03:50,490 --> 00:03:51,520
And all you have to do

126
00:03:51,520 --> 00:03:54,130
to attain this superior wisdom and knowledge

127
00:03:54,130 --> 00:04:00,020
is to call...in...sick.

128
00:04:05,690 --> 00:04:07,340
Okay. Okay. I will.

129
00:04:10,540 --> 00:04:13,330
Dr. Melendez. Got a case for you.

130
00:04:13,360 --> 00:04:14,820
My schedule's pretty packed today.

131
00:04:14,820 --> 00:04:18,200
It's a patient of mine. She needs a kidney transplant.

132
00:04:18,530 --> 00:04:19,490
You have a donor?

133
00:04:19,690 --> 00:04:22,040
Her identical twin -- a perfect DNA match.

134
00:04:22,180 --> 00:04:23,350
Why is she a patient of yours?

135
00:04:23,350 --> 00:04:26,030
I put balloon tissue expanders under both girls' scalps

136
00:04:26,030 --> 00:04:28,190
to prepare them for the separation surgery.

137
00:04:28,190 --> 00:04:29,790
Separation surgery?

138
00:04:34,780 --> 00:04:37,580
It's in six months, after they recover from the transplant.

139
00:04:38,080 --> 00:04:39,280
Of course, if you're too busy...

140
00:04:39,280 --> 00:04:40,830
No. I'm in.

141
00:04:44,360 --> 00:04:46,970
- Where's Murphy? - He's not here yet.

142
00:04:46,970 --> 00:04:49,270
Wrong day to be late. We're already shorthanded.

143
00:04:50,710 --> 00:04:53,380
- Actually, I wanted to talk to you about that. - I did not fire Kalu.

144
00:04:53,420 --> 00:04:55,430
And if you have a problem with it, talk to Andrews.

145
00:04:55,510 --> 00:04:58,750
Although, if you want my advice, don't have a problem with it.

146
00:05:00,020 --> 00:05:02,150
Andrews is waiting to brief us on a new case.

147
00:05:02,150 --> 00:05:05,750
It's a kidney transplant on craniopagus twins.

148
00:05:06,170 --> 00:05:07,280
Conjoined?

149
00:05:07,280 --> 00:05:08,670
They're connected at the skull.

150
00:05:08,670 --> 00:05:11,410
Their entire renal-vascular systems are interdependent.

151
00:05:12,120 --> 00:05:12,900
Cool.

152
00:05:13,720 --> 00:05:15,670
Have either of you talked to Shaun?

153
00:05:15,680 --> 00:05:17,990
- No. - No, which isn't unusual.

154
00:05:18,990 --> 00:05:19,890
Is anything wrong?

155
00:05:20,520 --> 00:05:23,220
No, no, not with Shaun. It's a family emergency.

156
00:05:23,220 --> 00:05:24,760
He's gonna be out for a few days.

157
00:05:24,770 --> 00:05:26,110
He's supposed to get approval

158
00:05:26,110 --> 00:05:27,820
for any personal days from his attending.

159
00:05:27,820 --> 00:05:29,210
Right, which is why I'm checking in.

160
00:05:29,210 --> 00:05:31,770
I think he thought it was enough just to notify me.

162
00:05:44,350 --> 00:05:45,420
You call in sick?

163
00:05:47,710 --> 00:05:49,570
I'm ready to go.

164
00:05:52,480 --> 00:05:53,690
No, you're not.

165
00:05:58,390 --> 00:06:01,070
You're gonna need more than a family photo and a toothbrush.

166
00:06:01,080 --> 00:06:01,840
Go pack.

167
00:06:01,840 --> 00:06:03,070
Uh, where are we going?

168
00:06:03,070 --> 00:06:04,410
Wherever the car takes us.

169
00:06:04,410 --> 00:06:05,450
I don't like the beach.

170
00:06:05,450 --> 00:06:07,340
Okay, I will let the car know.

171
00:06:08,980 --> 00:06:11,040
Even with your cardiovascular issues,

172
00:06:11,040 --> 00:06:13,780
a kidney transplant is a relatively safe procedure,

173
00:06:13,780 --> 00:06:15,610
especially since, with identical twins,

174
00:06:15,610 --> 00:06:17,240
there's no chance for organ rejection.

175
00:06:17,240 --> 00:06:19,620
Just make sure you keep straight which one's which.

176
00:06:19,620 --> 00:06:23,250
The charming, pretty one has the good kidneys.

177
00:06:23,250 --> 00:06:25,800
Don't worry. We always triple confirm.

178
00:06:25,800 --> 00:06:28,120
And we put everything in writing.

179
00:06:28,120 --> 00:06:30,080
And you're both charming and pretty.

180
00:06:30,350 --> 00:06:31,620
It was a joke, Mom.

181
00:06:31,620 --> 00:06:32,990
And smart.

183
00:06:32,990 --> 00:06:34,800
They're gonna be Ivy Leaguers in the fall.

184
00:06:34,800 --> 00:06:36,250
Yale and Harvard.

185
00:06:36,910 --> 00:06:38,850
Mom, you don't have to tell everyone you meet

186
00:06:38,850 --> 00:06:41,130
- where we're going to college. - Yes, I do.

187
00:06:41,130 --> 00:06:43,790
That's awesome. Congratulations.

189
00:06:44,380 --> 00:06:46,250
So, who's going where?

190
00:06:46,250 --> 00:06:48,280
What do you think? She's totally obnoxious

191
00:06:48,280 --> 00:06:50,140
and thinks she's way funnier than she is.

192
00:06:50,140 --> 00:06:51,290
Definitely Harvard.

193
00:06:52,410 --> 00:06:55,530
Hey, don't make me start mocking your tattoo.

194
00:07:00,230 --> 00:07:02,000
I thought you would have your entire apartment

195
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:03,130
strapped to your back.

196
00:07:03,170 --> 00:07:06,020
- It takes me a long time to pack. - ‭That's good.

197
00:07:06,100 --> 00:07:08,660
An anal-retentive packer is the exact type of person

198
00:07:08,660 --> 00:07:09,980
I'd want operating on me.

199
00:07:09,980 --> 00:07:12,240
Lea, this -- this is your car.

200
00:07:12,240 --> 00:07:13,910
Yeah, yeah, yeah. We're gonna take my other one.

201
00:07:14,340 --> 00:07:17,520
Okay. What do you do at work?

202
00:07:18,140 --> 00:07:20,700
Do you really care what I do, or do you just want to know

203
00:07:20,700 --> 00:07:23,960
how someone with such a crappy apartment can afford two cars?

204
00:07:23,960 --> 00:07:28,010
I just want to know how you can afford two cars.

205
00:07:29,840 --> 00:07:31,480
Yeah, I can't.

206
00:07:31,600 --> 00:07:33,250
Uh, my Grandpa Rod died last year,

207
00:07:33,250 --> 00:07:36,640
and he left me his most prized possession.

208
00:07:39,480 --> 00:07:41,350
It's the S-Striped Tomato.

209
00:07:42,360 --> 00:07:44,240
Oh, my God. You like "Starsky & Hutch"?

210
00:07:44,240 --> 00:07:45,410
It's okay.

211
00:07:45,540 --> 00:07:48,860
A meticulous packer and a "Starsky & Hutch" fan.

212
00:07:48,860 --> 00:07:50,610
Grandpa Rod would have loved you.

213
00:07:58,160 --> 00:08:01,530
Okay. This is it. The road.

214
00:08:01,530 --> 00:08:03,130
You sure you want to do this?

215
00:08:03,160 --> 00:08:05,700
Speak now or forever hold your peace.

216
00:08:07,480 --> 00:08:08,520
I'm sure.

217
00:08:10,290 --> 00:08:11,960
Let's go, Lea.

218
00:08:14,420 --> 00:08:16,190
Here we go!

219
00:08:25,830 --> 00:08:27,410
I hear Murphy's AWOL.

220
00:08:28,030 --> 00:08:30,020
He's taking a few personal days.

221
00:08:30,410 --> 00:08:31,670
Unapproved personal days.

222
00:08:31,670 --> 00:08:32,700
I approved them.

223
00:08:32,700 --> 00:08:34,390
It's not your job to approve them.

224
00:08:34,570 --> 00:08:37,260
Or to say you approved them to cover up the fact

225
00:08:37,260 --> 00:08:40,670
that Murphy's frequent tardiness has escalated to absences.

226
00:08:41,620 --> 00:08:43,490
What do you want me to do, take a polygraph?

227
00:08:43,940 --> 00:08:45,990
How about we jump into enhanced interrogation?

228
00:08:45,990 --> 00:08:47,890
Here, how about this? Do you want me to turn this on?

229
00:08:49,410 --> 00:08:51,930
When the board was reconsidering your hiring of Murphy,

230
00:08:51,930 --> 00:08:56,340
you assured us that if he was anything less than excellent,

231
00:08:56,530 --> 00:08:58,560
he'd be dismissed and you would resign.

232
00:08:58,560 --> 00:08:59,990
I trust you remember that.

233
00:09:00,060 --> 00:09:03,270
I wouldn't have your movers pack up your office just yet.

234
00:09:03,840 --> 00:09:05,080
You can't protect Murphy forever.

235
00:09:05,090 --> 00:09:09,720
At some point, he needs to succeed or fail on his own.

236
00:09:14,600 --> 00:09:16,990
Okay, that's three hours on the warm ischemia clock

237
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:18,850
of the transplanted kidney.

238
00:09:19,120 --> 00:09:21,570
The ureter is attached to the bladder.

239
00:09:22,090 --> 00:09:24,290
How's the kidney's placement in the iliac fossa?

240
00:09:26,880 --> 00:09:29,440
No kinking or twisting of the renal vessel.

241
00:09:29,440 --> 00:09:30,170
Good.

242
00:09:33,070 --> 00:09:34,250
You ready to close?

243
00:09:35,580 --> 00:09:36,450
Yes.

244
00:09:39,130 --> 00:09:42,200
Your best bet is a continuous suture along the fascial layer.

245
00:09:42,210 --> 00:09:42,920
Suture.

246
00:09:47,720 --> 00:09:49,070
Donor's pressure's dropping.

247
00:09:49,070 --> 00:09:50,480
Okay, up the oxygen.

248
00:09:50,480 --> 00:09:51,990
Jenny must be bleeding internally.

249
00:09:51,990 --> 00:09:53,330
We're gonna have to open her back up.

250
00:09:53,340 --> 00:09:54,490
Staple remover.

251
00:10:02,050 --> 00:10:04,150
I like trees.

252
00:10:04,660 --> 00:10:06,530
Yeah? What else do you like?

253
00:10:06,530 --> 00:10:08,220
Besides reading medical journals

254
00:10:08,220 --> 00:10:11,090
and watching reruns of old cop shows?

255
00:10:12,020 --> 00:10:13,160
I like you.

256
00:10:13,480 --> 00:10:15,930
Well, who wouldn't? I'm very likeable.

257
00:10:16,150 --> 00:10:18,820
Why don't you like San Jose?

258
00:10:18,850 --> 00:10:20,680
Everyone's so competitive here.

259
00:10:21,040 --> 00:10:23,840
You know, if you didn't make a million by 30,

260
00:10:23,840 --> 00:10:25,010
you're a total loser.

261
00:10:25,010 --> 00:10:26,840
I don't need $1 million.

262
00:10:27,380 --> 00:10:29,800
I don't even think I need $90,000, but...

263
00:10:30,520 --> 00:10:32,690
You know what we both need are some tunes.

264
00:10:32,690 --> 00:10:34,030
What's your preferred driving music?

265
00:10:34,040 --> 00:10:35,690
M-Music -- No. N--

266
00:10:35,700 --> 00:10:37,230
I don't like music. No. No.

267
00:10:37,230 --> 00:10:40,170
What? No, no. Not okay.

268
00:10:40,720 --> 00:10:43,070
Okay, I will give you a pass on not liking the beach

269
00:10:43,070 --> 00:10:43,990
because you're cute

270
00:10:43,990 --> 00:10:46,400
and I might need you to do brain surgery on me someday,

271
00:10:46,400 --> 00:10:49,790
but not liking music -- unacceptable.

272
00:10:49,790 --> 00:10:50,780
I won't have it.

273
00:10:50,780 --> 00:10:52,310
Are you being sarcastic?

274
00:10:52,310 --> 00:10:54,020
No. I'm being...

275
00:10:55,230 --> 00:10:57,990
I actually don't know the word for it, but my point stands.

276
00:10:57,990 --> 00:10:59,070
Music is amazing.

277
00:10:59,740 --> 00:11:02,030
You know, I remember every important thing

278
00:11:02,030 --> 00:11:03,330
that has ever happened to me

279
00:11:03,340 --> 00:11:07,040
based on what song I was listening to at the time.

280
00:11:07,240 --> 00:11:09,040
I remember smells.

281
00:11:09,630 --> 00:11:13,390
Like our parking garage smells like fabric softener,

282
00:11:13,390 --> 00:11:15,910
and when my brother died, it smelled like burnt food.

283
00:11:17,420 --> 00:11:20,410
Oh, my God. I'm so sorry. I had no idea.

284
00:11:21,620 --> 00:11:25,170
How did he, um... if you don't mind me asking?

285
00:11:27,330 --> 00:11:29,060
My father was mean.

286
00:11:30,130 --> 00:11:31,160
He killed my pet,

287
00:11:31,160 --> 00:11:34,590
so my brother and I, we ran away.

288
00:11:34,590 --> 00:11:36,530
Then he fell off a train we were playing on,

289
00:11:36,530 --> 00:11:38,030
hit his head, and died.

290
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:43,130
I never went back home.

